/Users/jake/chatgppt-lane-text-research-e2e/deck-scribe-craft-07/docs/live-evidence/lane-e-20260621/text-stage-deck_plan.json:8971:            "text": "{"markdown":"# DeckForge Plan\n\nApproved brief id: `lane_e_live_text_20260621_brief_live`\nApproved research pack: `rp_lane_e_20260621_solar`\nApproved research hash: `sha256:440b17df`\nAudience: climate-tech seed investors\n\n## Slide 1\n**Title:** Solar PV has already crossed from trend to infrastructure\n\n**Message:** Lead with scale. Show that global installed solar PV capacity expanded from **41.37146 GW in 2010** to **1,866.3064 GW in 2024** (about **45x** growth), establishing solar as a massive deployment platform rather than a niche energy source.\n\n**Build:**\n- Hero headline with one-line investor takeaway\n- Line chart: global installed solar PV capacity, 2010 to 2024\n- Right-side callout: “Scale is proven; the next bottleneck shifts to integration and storage”\n\n**Evidence:** Our World in Data, installed solar PV capacity dataset, captured in approved pack `rp_lane_e_20260621_solar`: World = `41.37146 GW` (2010), `1866.3064 GW` (2024), source id `src_solar_capacity`, dataset id `ds_solar_capacity_world`.\n\n## Slide 2\n**Title:** Module cost collapse makes downstream storage economics more investable\n\n**Message:** Show that solar's cost curve has structurally changed project economics. Global solar PV module cost fell from **2.4433622 USD/W in 2010** to **0.2579602 USD/W in 2024** (about **89% down**), which supports the thesis that value creation is moving toward balancing, dispatch, and storage layers.\n\n**Build:**\n- Downward line chart: module cost, 2010 to 2024\n- Two short bullets connecting cheaper generation to storage attach-rate logic\n- Bottom strip: “Falling generation cost shifts system value to flexibility”\n\n**Evidence:** Our World in Data, solar PV prices dataset, captured in approved pack `rp_lane_e_20260621_solar`: World = `2.4433622 USD/W` (2010), `0.2579602 USD/W` (2024), source id `src_solar_module_cost`, dataset id `ds_solar_module_cost_world`.\n\n## Slide 3\n**Title:** Non-hydro renewables are gaining share, reinforcing the flexibility gap\n\n**Message:** Close the 3-slide story by showing that non-hydro renewables are taking a larger share of electricity output globally, increasing the need for storage and grid-balancing solutions. Use the World Bank captured series carefully, noting that the approved artifact supports **2016 to 2021** and has null tail values after that.\n\n**Build:**\n- Line chart: global non-hydro renewable electricity share, 2016 to 2021\n- Annotation on the rise from **7.357428807255%** to **12.4213916892576%**\n- Closing takeaway: “More variable renewables in the mix increases the value of storage-enabled reliability”\n\n**Evidence:** World Bank indicator `EG.ELC.RNWX.ZS`, captured in approved pack `rp_lane_e_20260621_solar`: World non-hydro renewable electricity share = `7.357428807255%` (2016) and `12.4213916892576%` (2021), source id `src_worldbank_renewable_ex_hydro`, dataset id `ds_worldbank_renewable_ex_hydro_world`. The approved pack explicitly notes null values for 2022 to 2025 in the captured response."}",
/Users/jake/chatgppt-lane-text-research-e2e/deck-scribe-craft-07/docs/live-evidence/lane-e-20260621/text-stage-deck_plan.json:9101:    "markdown": "# DeckForge Plan

Approved brief id: `lane_e_live_text_20260621_brief_live`
Approved research pack: `rp_lane_e_20260621_solar`
Approved research hash: `sha256:440b17df`
Audience: climate-tech seed investors

## Slide 1
**Title:** Solar PV has already crossed from trend to infrastructure

**Message:** Lead with scale. Show that global installed solar PV capacity expanded from **41.37146 GW in 2010** to **1,866.3064 GW in 2024** (about **45x** growth), establishing solar as a massive deployment platform rather than a niche energy source.

**Build:**
- Hero headline with one-line investor takeaway
- Line chart: global installed solar PV capacity, 2010 to 2024
- Right-side callout: “Scale is proven; the next bottleneck shifts to integration and storage”

**Evidence:** Our World in Data, installed solar PV capacity dataset, captured in approved pack `rp_lane_e_20260621_solar`: World = `41.37146 GW` (2010), `1866.3064 GW` (2024), source id `src_solar_capacity`, dataset id `ds_solar_capacity_world`.

## Slide 2
**Title:** Module cost collapse makes downstream storage economics more investable

**Message:** Show that solar's cost curve has structurally changed project economics. Global solar PV module cost fell from **2.4433622 USD/W in 2010** to **0.2579602 USD/W in 2024** (about **89% down**), which supports the thesis that value creation is moving toward balancing, dispatch, and storage layers.

**Build:**
- Downward line chart: module cost, 2010 to 2024
- Two short bullets connecting cheaper generation to storage attach-rate logic
- Bottom strip: “Falling generation cost shifts system value to flexibility”

**Evidence:** Our World in Data, solar PV prices dataset, captured in approved pack `rp_lane_e_20260621_solar`: World = `2.4433622 USD/W` (2010), `0.2579602 USD/W` (2024), source id `src_solar_module_cost`, dataset id `ds_solar_module_cost_world`.

## Slide 3
**Title:** Non-hydro renewables are gaining share, reinforcing the flexibility gap

**Message:** Close the 3-slide story by showing that non-hydro renewables are taking a larger share of electricity output globally, increasing the need for storage and grid-balancing solutions. Use the World Bank captured series carefully, noting that the approved artifact supports **2016 to 2021** and has null tail values after that.

**Build:**
- Line chart: global non-hydro renewable electricity share, 2016 to 2021
- Annotation on the rise from **7.357428807255%** to **12.4213916892576%**
- Closing takeaway: “More variable renewables in the mix increases the value of storage-enabled reliability”

**Evidence:** World Bank indicator `EG.ELC.RNWX.ZS`, captured in approved pack `rp_lane_e_20260621_solar`: World non-hydro renewable electricity share = `7.357428807255%` (2016) and `12.4213916892576%` (2021), source id `src_worldbank_renewable_ex_hydro`, dataset id `ds_worldbank_renewable_ex_hydro_world`. The approved pack explicitly notes null values for 2022 to 2025 in the captured response."
